<TEXT>
defeated southern baptist moderates on 
wednesday weighed an uncertain perhaps separate future from their 
fundamentalistdominated convention as it undercut a 
religiousliberty agency in the nations capital 
unless the denominations ruling bloc becomes more inclusive and 
accepts the rest of us brothers and sisters some are going to 
leave said the rev daniel vestal defeated moderate candidate for 
the denominations presidency 
similar breakaway sentiments came from others in that camp 
which charges fundamentalists with using their appointive powers to 
control agencies and institutions of the 149millionmember 
denomination 
the rev morris chapman whose election as president tuesday 
extended fundamentalist control for a 12th straight year has 
supported moving the staff of the countrys largest protestant body 
toward a unanimous belief that the bible is errorfree 
the convention wednesday slashed support of the washingtonbased 
baptist joint committee on public affairs the influential 
religious liberty lobby of nine baptist groups for 50 years 
fundamentalists have assailed it for opposing prayer sponsored 
by public schools and for not fighting abortion 
the convention cut 87 percent of its support to the agency by 
shifting 346796 to the 13 million budget of the christian life 
commission in so doing it gave the job of lobbying for religious 
freedom to an agency whose primary mission is upholding morality 
with that change theyll laugh us off capitol hill said 
the rev ron sisk of tiburon calif 
the convention also gave some of the religious liberty function 
to the public affairs committee creating three perhaps 
conflicting voices 
the rev james dunn head of the baptist joint committee said 
it would keep up its defense of churchstate separation and against 
government intrusion into religion 
we wont downgade our religiousliberty agenda he said 
noting that assurances of supplemental financing were coming from 
state and local southern baptist churches across the country 
he told reporters that with the multiple agencies there likely 
will be contradictory testimony at times its something well 
have to live with 
the rev richard land head of the christian life commission 
said his agency shares the joint committees stand on churchstate 
separation and many other issues land predicted that conflicts 
will be far fewer than sometimes has been supposed 
but he added that there are many places where 
misinterpretation of supreme court decisions against sponsored 
school prayers have produced a brooding hostility to religion 
he said the greatest threat to religious liberty in the last 
decade of this century comes not from violation of the 
constitutions ban against establishing religion but from violating 
the reglious freeexercise guarantee 
he charged there were infringements and restraints on peoples 
religious conscience 
the rev grady cothen of coral springs fla head of of a newly 
formed religious liberty council to back the denominationally 
downgraded joint agency said the convention had turned a very 
sharp corner to the right 
it implies that the powersthatbe do not want to bring along 
the rest of us christian brethren they obviously want to be free 
of us but they wont make it 
however cothen former president of the denominations sunday 
school board added in an interview some will pull out its 
inevitable 
vestal trounced in an election in which chapman took 58 percent 
of the ballots by more than 38000 messengers said moderates 
soon would convene a meeting to consider their future 
let me confess some mystery about that future he told 
reporters its premature to talk about separation but he said 
there would be departures unless the current regime broadens its 
inclusiveness 
a lot of people are now ready to do something tangible to 
express their dicontent and alienation said the rev stan hastey 
of washington executive director of the baptist alliance they 
group was formed to pursue alternatives to the current 
denominational administration 
he said several moderate groups including the alliance baptist 
committed to the southern baptist convention and women in 
ministries would participate in the meeting about future steps 
probably in august 
