<TEXT>
abortion has emerged as one 
of the most emotional unification issues facing the germanys and 
people in both nations are debating which states abortion law 
should prevail 
west germany restricts abortions to three situtions medical 
necessity rape or incest and dire social or economic hardship in 
east germany first trimester abortions are performed costfree 
upon demand 
numbers reflect the widely varying laws 
in east germany with a population of 16 million 73000 
abortions were performed last year in west germany whose 
population is four times higher there were 75297 legal abortions 
east german doctors are prohibited from performing abortions on 
foreigners except in cases of emergency but pregnant west german 
women are already crossing the border hoping to take advantage of 
the looser law 
the two germanys plan to unite under the west german 
constitution as the quickest way to merge economic unity is to 
take place on july 2 and full union could come later this year 
the west german government led by chancellor helmut kohl says 
its constitution bars an abortion law such as east germanys 
the right of the unborn child to live is not open to question 
under our constitution said norbert greis a legal expert for 
west germanys christian social union the bavarian sister party to 
kohls christian democrats 
not everyone in kohls coalition agrees however 
west german justice minister hans engelhard has suggested two 
different abortion laws could exist for an interim period after 
unification the archconservative christian social union says that 
would be out of the question 
the west german social democrats say east germanys law is a 
good model for a united germanys abortion regulations arguing it 
places more importance on a womans rights 
women in east germany would certainly not abide seeing their 
longvalid abortion law fall victim to a harmonization of 
intergerman law said lawmaker renate schmidt a social democrat 
many east german women say hes right 
changing the abortion regulations would only bring trouble for 
us said a young pregnant east german woman registering for an 
abortion at a womens clinic in heiligenstadt a rural east german 
border town 
east germans are expected to face considerable economic hardship 
following unification because thousands of people are expected to 
lose their jobs and prices will soar many fear an abortion law 
like west germanys could increase the economic burden on families 
by forcing them to have unwanted children 
christa schmidt east germanys minister for family and womens 
affairs said she would not budge an inch on abortion rights 
although east german prime minister lothar de maiziere has not 
spoke out on the issue many members of his christian democratic 
union disagree with ms schmidt 
dr rudolf kessel chief doctor at the heiligenstadt clinic 
says he thinks east german women are too easygoing about abortions 
for a lot of women abortion is simply seen as a form of birth 
control especially in the big industrial cities this is the dark 
side of our law kessel said 
west germanys law passed in 1972 makes it extremely difficult 
for a woman to get an abortion those who request abortions on 
economic or social grounds must get two doctors to confirm their 
case is legitimate and must show proof of being counseled on 
adoption and welfare assistance 
in east germany a doctor can reject a request for an abortion 
only if the first 12 weeks of a pregnany have passed kessel said 
many west german women travel to the netherlands for abortions 
where the law is less strict some fear a type of abortion 
tourism will extend to east germany unless the nations bring 
their abortion laws into line 
abortion has long been a highly emotional issue in west germany 
last year the conviction of a prominent bavarian gynecologist 
caused a huge national stir and is still widely debated 
dr horst theissen found guilty by a bavarian court of failing 
to follow abortion guidelines was banned from practicing as a 
gynecologist for three years 
bavaria state predominantly catholic also tried 156 of 
theissens patients who were accused of having abortions under the 
hardship clause without proof of the required counseling most were 
fined up to 1600 
the trial resulted in charges among opposition politicians that 
west germanys abortion law was one of the most backward in 
europe 
abortion has not been such a heated issue in predominantly 
protestant east germany nonetheless there are strong 
antiabortion sentiments in roman catholic pockets such as 
heiligenstadt 
</TEXT>
