<TEXT>
east germanys leading political party has 
called for both german states to elect a single government in 
december 
the christian democrat caucus in parliament said tuesday that it 
would seek to have lawmakers vote on german unification this summer 
and that allgerman elections should be held no later than 
middecember 
chancellor helmut kohl of west germany has been pressing for 
allgerman elections in december in place of the west german 
elections set for dec 2 
east germany held its first free elections on march 18 ending 
four decades of communist rule 
east german prime minister lothar de maiziere the leader of the 
christian democrats has been noncommittal about holding december 
elections 
de maiziere was on a state visit to the united states on 
tuesday but guenther krause leader of the christian democratic 
faction in parliament said de maiziere favored the proposal 
krause said the christian democrats would soon begin talks on 
the proposal with other parties in their governing coalition which 
includes the leftleaning social democrats 
the east germany social democratic leader wolfgang thierse 
said his party opposes the elections because details of unification 
must first be worked out 
social democrats in both countries favor a slower pace for 
reunification while the conservative christian democrats have been 
seeking to move the process as quickly as possible 
many analysts believe kohl the leader of west germanys 
christian democrats would make a stronger showing in an allgerman 
balloting than in west german elections 
east germanys christian democrats enjoy a larger margin of 
support than their counterparts in west germany 
