<TEXT>
solomon b freehof a rabbi who was considered 
one of the worlds foremost reform jewish leaders died tuesday of 
an undisclosed cause at montefiore hospital he was 97 
freehof was elected president of the world union for progressive 
judaism in 1959 he was the first american accorded that honor 
which was seen as an acknowledgment of his stature in reform 
judaism 
he also was president of the central conference of american 
rabbis and as a member of the executive board of the union of 
american hebrew congregations he was honored in 1979 by the 
national conference of christians and jews 
a native of london freehof came to the united states in 1911 
he was an honors graduate of hebrew union college in cincinnati 
where he later taught and served as a jewish chaplain for american 
soldiers in europe during world war i 
freehofs first congregation was at the kehillath anshe mayriv 
temple in chicago which he left in 1934 to come to pittsburgh he 
served as rabbi at the rodef shalom temple in the citys shadyside 
neighborhood until his retirement in 1966 
on retiring he remembered his career this way its a happy 
profession provided that a man is suited for it and to whom public 
life is not a trial 
religion brings out the best side of people and the minister 
represents the best he said the ministry has become a public 
service 
freehof is survived by his wife lillian she is the author of 
more than 20 books of jewish legend and childrens stories 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

