<TEXT>
government officials say attorney general dick 
thornburgh acted within the law in heading discussions on revising 
the clean air act even though 20 percent of his assets are in 
stocks affected by the legislation 
president bush granted ethicslaw waivers to thornburgh last 
spring so the attorney general could head domestic policy council 
discussions leading to proposals to amend the clean air act 
administration officials said 
thornburgh needed the waivers because he held 149827 in stocks 
and bonds in 12 major industrial and oil companies and a public 
utility alvin a schall a thornburgh aide said tuesday 
these holdings amounted to 20 percent of the attorney generals 
assets of 722083 schall said 
federal conflictofinterest law bars highranking government 
officials from participating in decisions that would affect them 
personally 
but the law allows for granting waivers if the financial 
interest is not so substantial or was too remote or too 
inconsequential to affect the integrity of government officers or 
employees services 
you probably could make a pretty good argument that it isnt 
even necessary to get a waiver but just to be safe we did 
schall said 
he said the cleanair waivers were sought even though there was 
only a very attenuated relationship between any action the 
council might take on cleanair issues and the value of 
thornburghs investments 
the office of government ethics did not object to the waivers 
deputy director donald campbell said 
the statute allows the appointing authority in this case the 
president to find that a financial holding is not so substantial 
and significant as to affect performance campbell said 
if he was taking action that would specifically affect one of 
those companies a waiver is not the way to resolve it he added 
thornburgh obtained the cleanair waivers in may 1989 when the 
domestic policy council which he chairs was considering acid 
rain toxic emissions from factories and ozone pollution 
the attorney generals investments covered by the two waivers 
included holdings in four oil companies amoco corp atlantic 
richfield mobil corp and shell oil co and general motors 
general electric and westinghouse 
the other affected holdings were investments in wisconsin public 
service corp arco chemical corp black amp decker corp ppg 
industries inc procter amp gamble co and eastman kodak co 
the waiver for acidrain covered the wisconsin utility in which 
thornburgh has less than a 5000 investment the investments cited 
for a potential conflictofinterest in discussion of 
toxicemission issues amounted to 16 percent of the attorney 
generals assets holdings implicated by the ozone issue amounted 
to 4 percent of thornburghs assets schall said 
according to the financial statement thornburgh filed last 
month those holdings were worth between 109000 and 365000 or 
37 percent of an investment portfolio valued between 287000 and 
977000 
the financial disclosure law requires federal officials to 
report only broad ranges in the value of their stock and bond 
holdings schall provided the details on the value of the stock in 
oil and industrial companies at the time the waiver was granted 13 
months ago 
at that time thornburgh calculated the value of the affected 
holdings according to their current market value schall said 
thornburgh was also granted a waiver to participate in the 
drafting of legislation to ease antitrust restrictions to encourage 
the formation of jointproduction ventures schall said 
thornburgh cited holdings in american telephone amp telegraph co 
and international business machines corp as posing a potential 
conflict of interest the attorney generals holdings in each of 
the two companies is valued between 5000 and 15000 according 
to his latest financial disclosure statement 
the waiver to help write jointproduction legislation was sought 
because both atampt and ibm are involved in the research involving 
highdefinition television schall said 
thornburgh has shunned involvement in a number of issues because 
of his financial holdings 
