<TEXT>
president bushs string of successful vetoes 
remains unbroken but democrats are maneuvering for a second chance 
to force an amtrak aid bill into law over his objections 
bush emerged tuesday with the 11th veto of his term intact after 
democrats failed by three votes to muster the twothirds majority 
needed to override the presidents veto of a bill to support the 
rail service 
the president vetoed the 2 billion authorization bill last 
month because it also would have required that the interstate 
commerce commission approve acquisitions of major freight railroads 
by nonrailroad companies 
republicans promised during tuesdays debate that bush would 
support a substitute bill continuing support for the passenger rail 
service as long as the regulatory provision is omitted 
if they send us the bill without the icc provision hell sign 
it white house spokesman steve hart said after the 6436 vote 
sixtyseven votes were needed democrats will really only need 
to find two votes however since one of the 36 votes was that of 
majority leader george mitchell dmaine 
despite his desire to override the veto mitchell voted with 35 
republicans to sustain it since he was on the winning side 
mitchell is able under senate rules to call for a second vote if 
democrats can find the two extra votes needed to override 
those two votes will have to be republicans since all 55 
democrats in the senate have come out for the override there is no 
deadline for the second vote 
party pride was at stake said sen j james exon dneb 
i hope that we can get back not to whats nice for the party 
but what is right for america he said overriding this veto is 
certainly right for america and its transportation needs 
despite the victory it was the closest veto fight for bush so 
far in the house last week 58 republicans joined 236 democrats in 
voting to override the amtrak veto it was the first time either 
chamber had voted against the president a twothirds majority is 
needed in both chambers to override a veto 
republicans have introduced bills in both chambers to authorize 
federal spending for amtrak but without the regulatory provision 
that prompted the veto the senate version was introduced on the 
floor tuesday night by sen conrad burns rmont 
the bush administration and the reagan administration before it 
proposed to eliminate money for amtrak from all their budget 
requests the bill bush vetoed was not a funding bill but rather an 
authorization bill that means it gave congress permission to 
appropriate funds later for specific purposes 
the icc already must approve any sale of one railroad to 
another but supporters of the vetoed bill say the jurisdiction is 
needed over acquisitions by nonrailroad companies to prevent 
against the dismantling of railroad assets to pay for the takeovers 
what we want to avoid is a situation where people come in and 
buy the railroad and then just dismember it said sen paul 
simon dill 
in his veto message bush called the proposed icc oversight an 
unwarranted regulatory roadblock to the financial restructuring of 
the railroad industry 
