<TEXT>
although theyve been whipped in each and 
every veto showdown with president bush congressional democrats 
are showing no inclination to stay down on the mat for the 10count 
as the senate sustained bushs veto of bill to authorize 2 
billion for amtrak rail passenger service the house set up a veto 
fight with the white house over how much federal workers can 
participate in political campaigns 
by an overwhelming 33487 vote the house on tuesday rebuffed 
the administrations latest veto threat and sent bush a bill to 
allow federal workers to take an active role in partisan politics 
for the first time in more than half a century 
ninety or more than half of the houses 176 republicans 
including gop leader robert michel of illinois bolted from the 
administration in joining with 244 democrats to approve the changes 
in the 1939 hatch act 
the senate passed the same bill by a potentially vetooverriding 
6730 vote last month but gop leaders there have expressed 
confidence they can persuade enough colleagues to change votes to 
sustain a veto 
to win a veto fight bush must garner more than a third of the 
votes in either the house or senate as he did tuesday with 36 of 
the senates 100 members voted to sustain his veto of the amtrak 
bill 
in an effort to avoid another veto fight over the hatch law 
which outlaws most political activities for 3 million civil service 
and postal workers house leaders agreed to accept a senate version 
less onerous to the administration but still opposed by top 
administration aides 
many supporters of the changes had expressed a willingness to 
yield even further such as maintaining the current prohibitions 
for employees of intelligence agencies if the administration 
would only negotiate with them 
but attorney general dick thornburgh said in a letter tuesday 
that he and other senior advisers to bush oppose any change in the 
51yearold hatch law and would recommend that the president veto 
the bill 
such a reversal in the role of partisan politics in the ethic 
of public service would permit virtually unbridled partisan 
activities by federal employees thornburgh wrote 
unlike the original house bill last year the measure that 
congress is sending to bush retains current prohibitions against 
federal workers running for partisan office or soliciting campaign 
funds from the public 
if enacted government employees could begin holding office in 
local state and national political party organizations for the 
first time and solicit campaign funds from coworkers on behalf of 
federal employee union political action committees but only when 
not working 
the original house version approved by an overwhelming 29790 
vote in april 1989 would have allowed government workers to take 
leaves of absence to run for partisan office and solicit campaign 
funds from anyone 
we are not advocating the grey masses rising up in a 
coup said rep william ford dmich a sponsor of the bill 
were only asking for the simple right to put up a yard sign 
display a bumper sticker send a check or stuff envelopes 
the hatch law was enacted at the height of the new deal to 
protect a thenemerging professional civil service from being 
coerced by political appointees to contribute to or work on behalf 
of candidates 
opponents of changing the law argued that its protections 
against a spoils system are still needed 
</TEXT>
