<TEXT>
about half the american people believe the 
incurably ill and those hopelessly wracked with pain have a moral 
right to commit suicide according to a survey described as 
relevant to suicide doctor jack kevorkians case 
but an expert on the legal aspects of medical ethics says 
patients have absolutely no right to demand that a physician 
assist them in ending their lives 
thou shalt not kill still stands in this society 
especially for doctors susan m wolf a lawyer with the hastings 
center a research institute that studies medical ethics said in a 
telephone interview from briaircliff manor ny 
the poll conducted for the times mirror center for the people 
and the press showed that 49 percent of the public believe a 
person with an incurable disease has a moral right to commit 
suicide it said 55 percent believe in such a right for people 
suffering great pain with no hope of improvement 
the telephone poll of 1213 adults was conducted during the 
first week in may about a month before kevorkian touched off a 
furor by assisting in the suicide of a 54yearold woman who had 
been diagnosed as being in the early stages of alzheimers disease 
diane colasanto a researcher for the times mirror center said 
the survey did not include any questions about physicianassisted 
suicide but added i think what we found is relevant to the 
kevorkian case 
kevorkian a retired pathologist in pontiac mich created an 
intravenous device that he hooked up to janet adkins of portland 
ore at her request it allowed mrs adkins to press a button that 
fed coma and deathinducing drugs into her bloodstream 
kevorkian has not been charged and prosecutors say it may take 
up to two months to get results of toxicological studies of the 
dead womans brain to determine whether the alzheimers diagnosis 
was correct in the meantime circuit judge alice gilbert has 
ordered him to stop using his suicide machine and to refrain from 
doing anything else to help patients take their own lives 
the kevorkian case has demonstrated that there still is a lot 
of confusion among three very different things one being the right 
of a patient to commit suicide ms wolf said 
this question she said is distinct from whether a physician 
should be authorized to assist in a suicide and from the 
completely separate question of whether treatment should be 
terminated at the patients request 
the supreme court is expected to rule on the latter issue soon 
in the case of nancy cruzan 31 of carterville mo who suffered 
severe brain damage in a 1983 automobile accident her parents joe 
and joyce cruzan want doctors to remove a feeding tube from her 
stomach 
the feeding tube removal presented by the cruzan case has 
caused a lot of controversy in part because when you pull a 
feeding tube it is foreseeable often that the patient will indeed 
die said ms wolf 
however she said when a clinician honors a patients request 
to be free of an unwanted treatment he is essentially letting 
nature take its course 
there is a long history with ancient roots to the notion that 
people are entitled to be free of unwanted bodily invasion she 
said on the other hand people have absolutely no right to demand 
that a clinician assist them in suicide 
the times mirror poll showed that eight of 10 americans think 
patients should be allowed to die in some circumstances eight in 
10 also approved of state laws allowing medical treatment for a 
terminally ill patient to be withdrawn or withheld if that is what 
the patient wishes 
the poll was conducted may 15 the times mirror center an arm 
of the times mirror publishing and broadcasting organization said 
it was subject to a possible error of three percentage points 
either way because of sampling and other random effects 
