<TEXT>
state sen theo mitchells roots lie in a 
poor neighborhood of greenville but his political branches now 
stretch toward the governors mansion 
the 51yearold lawyer is hoping to become south carolinas 
first black governor on tuesday he became the first black in this 
century to head a major party ticket in south carolina when he 
earned the democratic gubernatorial nomination over freshman state 
sen ernest passailaigue 
if successful mitchell would be the second black elected 
governor in the country following l douglas wilders victory last 
year in virginia he enters the race an underdog to popular 
republican gov carroll campbell 
i dont think race will play any role mitchell said of the 
general election campaign and i dont think race should play any 
role 
mitchell grew up during the era of jim crow laws in a poor 
family dominated by his mother he played high school football with 
the rev jesse jackson who has endorsed his bid for governor 
he studied biology at fisk university in nashville tenn 
hoping to become a surgeon and transferred a year later to howard 
university he was the first member of his family to attend college 
and paid his tuition by working odd jobs 
after working in cancer research for five years at the national 
institutes of health in bethesda md he decided against medicine 
as a career and turned to law 
mitchell received his law degree from howard in 1969 and 
returned to greenville in 1970 to join a legal assistance program 
emphasizing poverty law he now heads his own firm 
in 1982 mitchell was indicted on charges of illegally receiving 
5390 in food stamps but a mistrial was declared when the jury 
could not reach a verdict and a retrial was never held mitchell 
has dismissed the case as political harassment 
he has served in the legislature since 1974 two years after he 
made an unsuccessful bid for congress after his first election he 
was reelected every two years until 1984 when he won election to 
the state senate 
mitchell has made health and human resource development his main 
campaign issues emphasizing help for the elderly and those in 
substandard housing he also supports extending public 
transportation around the state and says he would repeal the sales 
tax on food over a fiveyear period 
