<DOCNO> AP900613-0051 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the supreme soviet legislature has passed the 
countrys first press freedom law which gives any soviet citizen 
the right to found a newspaper and guarantees broad rights for 
journalists and publishers 
the new law which passed unanimously on tuesday intends to end 
decades of censorship of the soviet media by the communist party 
the government and a special agency established to kept the media 
under tight control 
the press and other mass media are free the law begins 
bluntly and censorship of the mass media is forbidden 
however the law does not address how those who want to publish 
their own newspapers will obtain newsprint which is often in short 
supply 
the soviet government controls all paper mills and the supply of 
newsprint and other materials needed to publish newspapers it also 
controls all radio and television stations 
after president mikhail s gorbachev came to power in 1985 and 
introduced the policy of glasnost or openess political pressure 
on the soviet media began to lighten but there was still no legal 
protection from interference 
technically freedom of the press is guaranteed by a declaration 
in the soviet constitution but tuesdays measure was the first law 
laying out detailed guarantees of press freedoms the tass news 
agency reported 
the law establishes procedures for creating media outlets and 
specifies journalists rights they include the right to attend 
meetings and be present at the scene of disasters the right to 
refuse to prepare reports that go against personal convictions and 
the right to interview officials 
the provision giving any individual the right to establish a 
media outlet created the sharpest debate in the supreme soviet 
tass reported 
however it was agreed that the right to establish a 
publication is one of the main democratic freedoms envisaged in the 
international covenants on human rights which the soviet union has 
joined and it is necessary to enforce them the staterun news 
agency said 
the law forbids publication of state secrets but tass said 
penalties would be imposed on the official who leaked them rather 
than the journalist who reported them 
it also forbids slander and use of the mass media to interfere 
in citizens private lives infringement on their honor and 
dignity 
pornography long outlawed in the soviet union remains illegal 
although soviet media including television have begun showing 
nudity fairly often 
the law a copy of which was obtained by the associated press 
does not specify the penalties for slander and other abuses of 
press freedoms saying they can be established by the courts 
according to existing or future laws 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

