<TEXT>
a study of premature babies of belownormal 
weight shows their iq can be boosted by special education in their 
first years 
loraine stern a pediatrician at the university of california at 
los angeles said the study in todays journal of the american 
medical association also showed the importance of parental 
involvement in a childs early years 
you cant recapture what you lose in the first few years 
she said 
in the fouryear study onethird of 985 babies born in 1985 in 
eight states received educational help researchers visited the 
home advised parents provided educational toys and arranged 
visits to a child development center 
infants who weighed between 44 and 55 pounds at birth and 
received educational help and medical care scored an average of 98 
at age 3 or 132 iq points higher than children who had been in 
the same weight range at birth but received only medical care the 
average iq is 100 
infants who weighed about 43 pounds or less at birth and were 
given the educational help scored an average of 91 at age 3 or 66 
iq points higher than similar infants getting only medical care 
wrote the researchers led by dr ruth gross of stanford university 
arnold sameroff a psychologist who teaches at brown university 
and practices at bradley hospital in providence ri said the 
children in the study got such multifaceted help other researchers 
will find it hard to tell what made the difference 
almost 7 percent of babies born in the united states or 250000 
a year weigh 55 pounds or less at birth though these 
lowbirthweight babies have a much better chance of survival than 
in years past they still are at risk of retarded development 
