demonstrators halted traffic in much of 
the capital today to protest the apparent victory of the heirs to 
the longruling communists in bulgarias first free elections in 58 
years 
the protesters formed barricades with benches blocking traffic 
on main thoroughfares including an intersection demonstrators had 
blocked for several hours tuesday night some threatened drivers 
who did not honk their horns 
honking has become a common expression of protest over the past 
few days against the socialist party known until april as the 
communist party 
with half the official results tallied the socialists appeared 
to have won the first round of voting on sunday but final results 
were not expected before tonight an election official said 
runoffs are being held sunday in 81 constituencies where no 
single candidate received the required majority 
analysts said that based on the known results and projections by 
west german and bulgarian groups it was still possible that the 
opposition could gain a slight edge after the secondround voting 
but the official bta news agency said the opposition would have 
to win nearly all the seats at stake in the runoffs 
half of parliaments 400 seats are being filled by direct 
election the other 200 based on the percentage of votes each party 
receives 
