<TEXT>
a nuclear weapon with up to 11 times 
the explosive force of the atomic bomb that devastated hiroshima 
was detonated underground wednesday at the nevada test site it was 
the second announced test this year 
stephen ledogar the us ambassador to the international 
conference on disarmament joined test controllers and other energy 
department officials in viewing the test by closedcircuit 
television at a control point 32 miles from ground zero 
the energy department announced monday that the test would have 
an explosive yield of 20 to 150 kilotons of tnt the bomb dropped 
on hiroshima in 1945 produced a blast of 13 kilotons 
tests are announced in advance when they will reach near the 
upper limits managers of highrises in las vegas are warned by the 
energy department not to have workers in precarious positions at 
the time of the blast all tests are announced as being less than 
20 kilotons or 20 to 150 kilotons 
the test was the first since march 10 
last year 12 nuclear weapons were exploded underground at the 
desert site in recent years the energy department has tested an 
average of about one nuclear weapon a month 
the test was the 701st since testing began at the site in 1951 
