<TEXT>
the soviet legislature voted to further speed the 
nation toward a market economy wednesday but a government official 
told lawmakers that an threefold increase in bread prices would be 
delayed 
panicbuying has emptied many store shelves since late last 
month when the communist government proposed to cut many price 
subsidies by january 
prices on bread the main staple of the soviet diet also will 
be raised eventually but of course not by july 1 said yuri 
maslyukov chairman of the government agency that runs the 
centralized economy bread now sells for less than 30 cents a loaf 
the supreme soviet ordering the finetuning of a plan that drew 
widespread criticism as being too vague and tentative instructed 
the council of ministers to have drafts of all the laws needed for 
the switch from a planned to a market economy by october 
the measure also instructed president mikhail s gorbachev to 
issue a series of presidential decrees beginning july 1 to speed up 
progress on bringing new laws on ownership leasing farming and 
other key elements of a market economy into effect 
the main thing now is that now we can begin to work said 
leading economist and deputy prime minister leonid abalkin 
three years ago someone who called for a market economy was 
pointed at theres a man whos betraying the ideals of 
socialism he said today everyones talking about how to make 
the transition faster 
abalkin speaking to reporters at the supreme soviet said the 
government still intends to raise most prices on retail goods and 
raw materials in january as stated in its earlier plan despite 
consumer outcry 
the supreme soviet heard maslyukovs proposal wednesday to 
postpone the price increase on bread and was expected to vote on it 
thursday 
maslyukov recommended the postponement largely because the plan 
for compensating the population for the extra money they would have 
to spend on bread still needed work but he said nine of the 15 
soviet republics already have agreed to increase their bread prices 
aug 1 with compensation beginning about two weeks earlier 
wednesdays resolution did not reject outright the program put 
forth by premier nikolai i ryzhkov late last month which focused 
on price rises but it demanded quick concrete plans for creating 
a market and immediate spending cuts on defense the government 
bureaucracy and construction to cut the budget deficit 
we have to begin work now deputy alexei boiko who 
presented the resolution told lawmakers 
ryzhkov and his government were forced to rethink the plan after 
it prompted panic buying and drew nearly unanimous criticism by 
economists around the world for raising prices without freeing 
enough goods and prices from government control to allow a true 
transition to a market economy 
wednesdays resolution set an october deadline for gorbachevs 
administration to hammer out concrete reforms including bills to 
create a stock market commercial banks credit and a federal 
reserve bank deputies changed the draft to remove the specifics of 
which laws were needed but said the list still applied 
ryzhkov told reporters he supported the altered plan the 
project was worked on by commissions and is fairly objective and 
allows us to work further he said 
but he said it would be difficult to complete all the laws and 
practical measures by the autumn deadline 
ryzhkov admitted he was surprised at the swell of sentiment 
against the price increases he said he knew it would be difficult 
but to tell the truth i thought society was more prepared 
asked about calls for his resignation due to the outcry ryzhkov 
said its not a question of who works on this program im 
convinced this is the road we have to take 
opposition economist gennady filshin criticized wednesdays 
proposal as a compromise among government economists unwilling to 
take the radical steps needed his interregional group the 
opposition in the soviet congress proposed much more radical 
measures including liquidating all ministries and freeing up 
prices altogether 
other deputies took the floor wednesday to blast the proposal as 
well many speaking against the overall price increases but the 
resolution passed nonetheless in a series of votes on each article 
boiko said the parliament would keep a close eye on the 
governments fulfillment of the resolution and if by fall it had 
not made satisfactory progress we will be forced to make the 
corresponding verdict 
