a prominent us monitoring group says police 
and members of the security forces are responsible for most human 
rights violations in mexico the official news agency notimex said 
americas watch said in a report made public wednesday that the 
war on drugs is often used as a pretext for murder torture and 
extortion 
it said the special antinarcotics division of the federal 
judicial police has one of the worst rights records especially in 
the northern states of sinaloa durango and chihuahua 
a spokesman for the mexican attorney generals office said 
tuesday night it had no comment on the report copies of which were 
released early the federal judicial police are an arm of the 
attorney generals office 
americas watch said that police and security force corruption 
and violence threaten mexicos national security 
the 115page report human rights in mexico a policy of 
impunity also said some rights violations are political 
it said labor strife election disputes and land battles which 
often pit the party that has ruled mexico for 61 years against its 
opponents have spawned assassinations disappearances and illegal 
detentions 
americas watch cited the cases of several journalists who have 
been murdered and said some of its informants had received threats 
from police officers 
the report by the new yorkbased group criticizes the united 
states for ignoring mexicos poor record on human rights it blamed 
the indifference on a desire for cordial relations with mexico 
