<TEXT>
terence oneill a former prime minister of 
northern ireland who attempted to reconcile protestants and roman 
catholics in the 1960s has died the government said wednesday he 
was 75 
oneill who served as the provinces prime minister from 
196369 died tuesday at his home in lymington hampshire 
britain suspended northern irelands parliament in 1972 in the 
the face of growing sectarian and political violence and instituted 
direct rule in 1973 
oneill was named a lord in 1970 and spoke frequently in 
britains house of lords on northern ireland 
irish prime minister charles haughey said of oneill he was a 
good man who meant well and perhaps if he had succeeded in the 
things he undertook the whole course of events in northern ireland 
might have been different 
irish deputy prime minister brian lenihan added he will 
always be remembered as the terence oneill in the 1960s who with 
irish prime minister sean lemass initiated certain historic 
attempts at reconciliation between all irish people 
oneill was born on sept 10 1914 into an aristocratic 
angloirish family 
he fought with the irish guards during world war ii and in 1946 
entered northern irelands parliament as a member of the 
predominantly protestant unionist party 
he succeeded lord brookeborough as prime minister in 1963 
soon after taking office he introduced reforms aimed at 
accommodating the growing political aspirations of the roman 
catholic minority he also worked to strengthen trade with ireland 
in january 1965 after a surprise visit by irish prime minister 
lemass to parliament angry protestant extremists who opposed a 
rapprochment with the predominantly catholic irish republic began 
an oneill must go campaign led by the rev ian paisley 
in 1968 friction between catholics and protestants escalated 
into violent riots in northern ireland convincing oneill of the 
need for reform 
he faced opposition from his home secretary william craig who 
demanded strong police action against civil rights demonstrators 
oneill fired craig and instituted a number of reforms to aid 
the catholic community including changes in local administration 
frustrated by critics who feared the loss of british 
sovereignty oneill called a general election in february 1969 he 
managed to win leadership of his badly split party but resigned 
two months later 
jack lynch irish prime minister from 196673 described oneill 
as a man of courage and vision 
its a great pity that he was unable to bring the majority of 
his cabinet along with him in his reforms he clearly wanted 
to see the people of all ireland north and south live in peace 
friendship and economic well being lynch said 
oneill is survived by a wife the former katherine jean 
whitaker and a son and daughter 
</TEXT>
