liberian government and rebel 
delegations met for six hours wednesday and agreed to an appeal 
from liberias religious leaders to end attacks on civilians 
a joint statement signed by both sides made no reference to 
church leaders request for an immediate ceasefire in the 
5monthold civil war but it said an end to attacks on 
noncombatants will go a long way in enhancing the peace process 
now successfully under way 
more than 1000 people have been killed many of them civilians 
since the rebel national patriotic front moved into liberia from 
the ivory coast on dec 24 and began a drive on monrovia the 
liberian capital 
wednesday was the second day of talks mediated by the liberian 
council of churches at a us embassy auditorium in the sierra 
leone capital talks will resume thursday 
both sides signed the statement which called for an immediate 
end to the killings molestation and destruction of properties and 
innocent civilians and other noncombatants 
it said the government and insurgents strongly condemned the 
killing harassment and destruction of properties of unarmed 
civilians as such acts will not benefit any side since there can 
be no winners in this fracticidal war 
the statement also said negotiators approved an agenda for 
substantive talks leading to the peaceful resolution of the 
confict 
no mention was made of the demand by rebel leader charles taylor 
that president samuel doe resign and leave liberia before 
negotiations could proceed 
