<DOCNO> AP900613-0192 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
parliament has made drug use a crime in italy in an 
effort to stem an increasing number of overdose deaths and 
narcoticsrelated crimes opponents said the new law infringes on 
personal liberties 
since 1975 italy has had a much more permissive attitude toward 
drug use than most western european countries that law allowed 
possession of a moderate amount of drugs for personal use 
it also left a loophole that permitted many sellers caught by 
the police to claim drugs in their possession were for personal use 
the new law adopted by parliament on tuesday makes it illegal to 
use drugs in all amounts though it remains lenient for those 
caught with no more than a daily dose 
in the case of such small amounts no penalties will be applied 
for those who choose to undergo rehabilitation the precise amount 
of a daily dose will be defined later 
if the user refuses treatment however his drivers license and 
passport can be suspended up to three months further abuse can 
bring jail up to three months 
the new law also stiffens penalities for drug dealing those 
convicted of trafficking in heroin or cocaine can be sentenced to 
eightto20 years in prison and fined up to 420000 the old laws 
maximum penalty was 15 years and 83500 
the new law was adopted to combat a wave of social problems 
related to drug use 
overdose deaths roughly doubled from 1987 to 1989 this years 
total is expected to be even higher about 1000 
also worrisome has been the spread of aids through contaminated 
needles throwing a syringe away in a public place now can bring a 
fine of up to 835 
also under the new law marijuana users caught for the first 
time will be issued a warning 
the list of prohibited drugs includes heroin cocaine 
hallucinogens marijuana and hashish as well as amphetamines and 
barbituates in amounts above medical doses 
opponents say the new law violates their civil liberties 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

