<TEXT>
islamic fundamentalists who won a 
majority of local council seats in algerias first multiparty 
elections demanded wednesday that parliament be dissolved so they 
can move to take national power 
the victory by the islamic salvation front in the nationwide 
local elections marks a stunning triumph for islamic hardliners 
and their 16monthold party 
a day after the vote the fundamentalists called on president 
chadli bendjedid to hold national elections within three months 
instead of february 1992 as scheduled the government had no 
immediate response 
the national liberation front had been widely expected to win 
tuesdays voting because of its grip on government machinery and 
the media as well as its greater financial resources it holds 
every seat in parliament 
but on wednesday before any official results were released 
interior minister mohamedsalah mohammedi announced the 
fundamentalist islamic salvation front had won a majority of the 
15000 seats at stake on 1541 municipal and 48 provincial councils 
first official results released later wednesday more than 24 
hours after the voting ended showed the fundamentalists captured 
327 of the 612 municipal council seats counted so far the 
governing party won 208 seats or 33 percent 
the interior minister said the partial official returns 
indicated the anticlerical rally for culture and democracy had won 
51 seats in tuesdays voting with independents and the tiny 
national party for solidarity and development taking the rest 
the interior minister said complications had delayed the count 
and full results would be unavailable before thursday 
the french news agency agence francepresse citing sources 
said the fundamentalists captured councils in algerias four 
largest cities algiers oran constantine and annaba and swept 
45 of the 48 provincial councils 
