<TEXT>
the telephone message slips were 
piling up on lobbyist loren smiths desk the callers were state 
legislators and their message was written between the lines they 
wanted money 
smith looked across the big wooden desk across his spacious 
modern office and out the windows that framed the state capitol 
gleaming in the sun after 25 years as a lobbyist he was troubled 
by what he saw 
like most lobbyists smith helps his clients dole out campaign 
contributions to legislators its a role that empowers lobbyists 
guarantees their telephone calls will be returned and their faces 
remembered when they argue for their clients interests it can 
give them influence beyond that of the voters whom legislators 
ostensibly serve 
but increasingly it is giving them pause 
legislators appetites for campaign funds are insatiable and 
lobbyists say they cant fill the lawmakers plates fast enough 
ive never had to buy a vote in my life nor do i intend to 
said smith whose clients include such corporate giants as dow 
chemical and pillsbury 
and yet he feels intense pressure to give money to legislators 
the unspoken implication is that hell lose his influence if he 
doesnt 
the pressure for money doesnt come from us he said im 
not running over there he gestures toward the capitol 
saying can i give you some money for a vote im saying 
and now he slaps his forehead oh god another request 
other lobbyists say the same thing and not just in sacramento 
across the nation legislative campaign spending is careening out 
of control and lobbyists cant or wont stop stoking the 
engines 
the problem is that the legislators have gotten as greedy as 
the lobbyists said state sen julian l lapides of maryland 
the cost of running for public office has risen ever faster in 
the past decade pulled by the lure of television advertising and 
pushed by the stick of competition 
legislative campaign expenses in california rose 180 percent 
between 1978 and 1988 the average race cost 610000 by the end of 
that period no other state is so costly but campaign spending is 
the talk of statehouses from coast to coast 
campaign expenses rose 442 percent in alaska between 1976 and 
1988 costs doubled in new jersey between 1983 and 1987 quadrupled 
in illinois between 1980 and 1988 and quintupled for washington 
state senate races between 1976 and 1986 
it is out of hand theres no question about it said h 
donald stewart a new jersey lobbyist who formerly served in that 
states assembly when he first ran for office 25 years ago 
25000 was considered a huge campaign warchest 
today they make that on one fundraiser stewart said and 
then they have a long way to go 
in the trade route of campaign finance moneyed interests are on 
one coast and politicians on the other lobbyists navigate between 
the two they advise clients on how much to give and to whom and 
they frequently deliver the money 
maryland lobbyist bruce bereano figures hell have a hand in 
dispensing 150000 in campaign funds this year thats a 
conservative figure he added it depends on how the races 
shape up 
those with money arent necessarily picky about who gets it 
frequently lobbyists will recommend that clients give to both 
candidates in a close race just to make sure they help out the 
winner 
its like going to the racetrack and making a bet after the 
race said barry kauffman of pennsylvania common cause which 
lobbies for open government and is critical of lobbyists influence 
lobbyists in most states also buy tickets to legislative 
fundraising parties which have become almost nightly events in 
most state capitals 
in sacramento or albany ny tickets to fundraisers are 
frequently 500 or 1000 each and lobbyists can be invited to as 
many as five or six in an evening richard dugally a lobbyist for 
ford motor co in sacramento figured he could have spent 105000 
in 1988 by buying one ticket to every fundraiser he was asked to 
attend he bought none because its fords policy not to do so 
in some states lobbyists are asked to do more than just buy 
tickets theyre expected to sell them too lapides the maryland 
legislator said some of his colleagues expect lobbyists to sell as 
many as 200 tickets each to fundraisers 
a lobbyist can then become the prime fundraiser for a 
legislator lapides said a legislator would find it impossible 
to view them or legislation that the lobbyist has before that 
legislator objectively 
that gets to the heart of the issue that lobbyists exert 
influence beyond that of an ordinary voter 
most say their influence derives from the interest groups they 
represent not the money they spend and at least some of the time 
thats true 
in california environmental lobbyists exert a powerful 
influence despite being outspent by wealthier opponents in 
delaware legislators say the most powerful lobbyists are those who 
represent volunteer firefighters whose ladders of influence extend 
to nearly every home in the state 
lobbyists say campaign contributions dont buy votes they buy 
access or a friendly relationship or a sympathetic ear 
yet there is sometimes a fine line between access and influence 
last year oregon state sen wayne fawbush disappointed 
environmentalists by voting against a bill to protect a stand of 
oldgrowth trees a bill that fawbush considered a leading 
preservationist had sponsored 
later it was revealed fawbush had received 12000 in campaign 
contributions from the timber industry the previous election year 
it tells us that the thousands of dollars he took from the 
timber industry counted when the chips were down said terry 
nelson the former executive director of oregon common cause 
fawbush denied he had sold his vote but conceded campaign 
contributions buy influence 
if you have a large contributor its only human nature that 
youre going to listen to them he said but listening cant be 
equated to being bought 
in new mexico state sen shannon robinson said he hadnt been 
getting contributions from oil and gas companies until he 
introduced a resolution calling on the state to study them right 
away the money started flowing in he said 
i had to express an interest in an industry in order to get 
that industrys support robinson said 
in that instance the resolution didnt benefit the industry and 
had no binding effect robinson said he always has the best 
interest of voters at heart and hasnt changed a vote because of 
the financial influence of a lobbyist 
still he said you get that kind of money and you think twice 
about the commitment those people made and you try to help them 
with your vote when you can 
nevada assemblyman jim banner said he cared deeply about what 
his constituents had to say but constituents were rarely among his 
major campaign donors and aside from a few zealots he rarely 
heard from the people in his district 
i like to feel clean about it banner said before he retired 
this year but hell a lot of times i push that button and i have 
no idea what my constituents want 
</TEXT>
