<TEXT>
there are no college degrees in legislative lobbying no 
entrance exams and no written qualifications but there is one sure 
way to become a lobbyist become a legislator first 
in nearly every state the ranks of the most successful 
lobbyists are filled with former legislators former legislative 
aides and the occasional former governor or congressman just as 
those with money are attracted to the power of legislators so are 
legislators attracted to the allures of money 
its hardly surprising the highest paid legislators those in 
new york state earn under 60000 a year the lowest paid those 
in new hampshire earn a token 100 a year 
good lobbyists in almost any state can earn more than 100000 a 
year in the biggest states they can become millionaires 
we resent it said alaska state senate president tim kelly 
who earns about 30000 a year the disparity between the 
legislator and the lobbyist is outrageous 
but many legislators swallow their resentment and walk through 
the revolving door 
there are more than two dozen former legislators working as 
lobbyists in oklahoma at least 50 in texas 35 in illinois 28 in 
new mexico when the north carolina center for public policy 
research ranked lobbyists in that state according to their clout 
six of the top 10 and eight of the top 15 were former legislators 
in some states such as oklahoma and south carolina former 
legislators have at least one advantage over other lobbyists they 
are allowed onto the floor of the legislature during sessions 
these other guys have to stay out there in the foyer said 
south carolina rep herb kirsh these guys can come in sit down 
kneel by your desk and talk to you 
beyond that former legislators bring a wealth of advantages to 
the lobby they know the names and faces they know how laws are 
made they know how the political game is played 
