<TEXT>
if ronald reagans new federalism did nothing 
else it taught washingtons lobbying corps that there is life 
and politics outside the beltway 
a surge of activity in state capitols has set off a political 
equivalent of the gold rush washington lobbyists flocking to 
lucrative diggings in jefferson city and juneau sacramento and 
santa fe boston and baton rouge 
they have worked quietly often unseen but they have brought a 
new sophisticated style of politics to state capitals where 
oldfashioned shoeleather lobbying is now augmented by television 
ad campaigns and computergenerated grassroots organizing 
theres been a huge explosion of interest in the state 
level said paul hallman one of the founding partners of 
multistate associates a lobbying firm with offices in washington 
and great neck ny 
multistate which may be the largest firm of its type maintains 
a roster of 1500 local lobbyists in all 50 states it hires them 
out to such clients as apple computer bristolmyers citicorp 
johnson amp johnson metropolitan life nabisco playtex procter amp 
gamble and union carbide 
you can come to us and we can reach out anywhere in the 
country said steve markowitz the firms other founding partner 
multistate established in 1984 was among the first national 
lobbying firms to capitalize on the state legislative bonanza but 
it is not alone 
hill amp knowlton the huge public relations firm recently 
entered the competition by buying out an established lobbying 
company hoog amp associates of boulder colo 
tom hoog a former aide to sen gary hart who founded the firm 
now works for hill amp knowlton as a senior vice president so far 
this year he said hill amp knowlton has been active in 34 or 35 
states and monitors legislation in all 50 he wouldnt name the 
companys clients 
hill amp knowlton has offices in only two state capitals denver 
and tallahassee fla but hoog said that will change soon as i 
look down the road a couple years i see us opening offices in 10 
to 15 capitals minimum he said 
special interest groups and corporations too are sending their 
own lobbyists into the states in growing numbers the states are 
the battlefield said florida lobbyist lee moffitt the real 
power is in the legislature 
the actual number of bills considered by legislatures has 
remained about the same the past decade it hovers around 200000 
a year for all 50 states according to the national conference of 
state legislatures 
but the nature of the bills has changed the issues are bigger 
the stakes higher smoking abortion assault rifles toxic waste 
tort reform aids all are issues that once might have fallen 
solely under the purview of the federal government now each can be 
found on the agenda of nearly every legislature 
some credit president reagans new federalism with stimulating 
statehouse lobbying by restoring power and responsibility to the 
states 
by that yardstick youd have to say he was a major success 
because issues did move to the states said hoog 
not that the federal government withered it grew larger than 
ever in the reagan years but the reagan administration certainly 
relinquished responsibility for some domestic tasks and many 
critics say the congress became a more difficult place to do 
business more politically charged less open to consensus 
richard gardiner head of state government relations for the 
national rifle association calls the new federalism a lot of 
baloney 
i think that the answer is that those who believe in more 
regulation have decided that the states are the next fertile field 
the federal government cant do anything more theyve regulated so 
much theres nothing left to regulate he said 
gardiner speaks with some bitterness his group has lost some 
tough battles over the right to own semiautomatic weapons still 
the nra can claim one of the most impressive track records of any 
lobbying group it combines the tactical savvy of nine seasoned 
lobbyists with the grassroots clout of nearly 3 million members 
the nras legislative lobbyists are the paratroopers of 
politics there are seven in washington covering the eastern 
twothirds of the nation and two in sacramento calif covering 
the western third they spend their days zooming from one capital 
to the next in a neverending war against gun control 
our lobbyist for new england for example will go up to 
albany new york for an afternoon take a flight over to portland 
or augusta maine spend the next morning there and then go down to 
rhode island that afternoon and then zip over to connecticut 
and come home gardiner said 
nra lobbyists are backed up by a grassroots organizing machine 
that is the envy of lobbyists everywhere the nra spends millions 
of dollars sending mail to its members who respond with letters 
telephone calls and personal visits to legislators 
that kind of support is what other lobbyists are trying to 
cultivate 
once grassroots suggested a brand of politics that was 
unsophisticated unplanned and inexpensive a spontaneous movement 
on behalf of a candidate or cause 
now with the help of the imagemakers grassroots lobbying can 
be slick calculated and costly 
its aim is to persuade legislators that a lobbyists position 
has popular support the techniques can be as simple as a letter to 
citizens asking them to call or write their legislators they can 
be as sophisticated as television commercials that subtly shift the 
public mood 
i hate for anybody to refer to me as just a lobbyist anymore 
because i dont think theres a market for just straight 
lobbying said hill amp knowltons hoog i think you have to 
provide a base of support for your position 
gary nordlinger is a specialist in drumming up that support his 
washington office is dominated by a large wooden bookcase filled 
not with books but with audio and video tapes they represent his 
most tangible product 
one videotape is a commercial produced for the nevada state 
education association several years ago to bolster its clout at the 
legislature viewers were shown images of state prison inmates the 
point nevadans could spend money on schools now or prisons later 
its now becoming increasingly common to do in a state capital 
whats been done in congress which is not only to use your 
lobbyist but to rally public support to run advocacy media to do 
grassroots lobbying as well to get people to contact their 
legislators nordlinger said 
legislatures can be a lot more fun to work than the congress 
too you know if the congress is a fullblown railroad a 
state legislature is much more like a model train much easier to 
have a big impact 
</TEXT>
