<TEXT>
panamas justice system once 
considered the lapdog of a corrupt military now is accused of 
being a glacially slow institution whose prosecutors take bribes to 
bury cases 
of more than 5000 cases received by the attorney generals 
office in the first four months of 1990 after the us invasion 
that ousted gen manuel antonio noriega none had gone to court by 
early june 
edgardo molino mola a supreme court justice told reporters 
more than 13000 cases were pending in one judicial district where 
the number of judges was fixed by law at 53 
opinions on how to change the situation range from revising the 
law on judicial procedures to requiring that all judges have some 
legal training 
deputy prosecutor rosa de contreras told the associated press 
the problem is not with the prosecutors but with the law that 
establishes court terms we must follow the law has not been 
changed 
juan materno vasquez former chief justice of the supreme court 
said the law is fine but complained of inexperience and a lack 
of technical preparation of appointed judges some of whom have 
never even been lawyers 
molino mola said more judges and courtrooms were needed 
in san milguelito a workingclass suburb of panama city he 
said there are 1200 cases pending before just one judge as for 
justice people are disgusted with notorious criminals going free 
on bond 
they worry about the slow pace of the judicial process the 
lack of prosecution of embezzlers and torturers and that because 
of bungled prosecutions the courts have had to free some people 
he said in a statement 
his remarks were published by the civic crusade an organization 
of business and professional people that led the panamanian 
