<TEXT>
americas colleges increasingly concerned about 
gang and acquaintance rape are starting to teach students a more 
elemental lesson than english lit and geology 101 that it takes 
two to say yes to sex 
at campuses around the country schools are sponsoring hotlines 
courses and workshops to counter the widespread conviction that 
when it comes to sex its every man for himself 
many campus males feel you should always be ready to have sex 
even if you dont want to says toby simon assistant dean of 
student life at brown university dont ask a woman how far you 
can go just start making moves 
four years ago simon surveyed students to learn if theyd ever 
had sex against another persons will ten percent of the men at 
a school where students have a tendency to be politically 
correct admitted they had 
that to me was a real trigger that we had to do something 
said simon who also is director of health education 
at the time few schools admitted a problem existed but simons 
efforts put brown in the forefront of sex crime education 
now slowly other schools are following that lead and as 
awareness grows it appears more victims are coming forward and 
are being taken seriously 
bernice sandler director of the association of american 
colleges project on the status of women has documented about 100 
campus gang rapes nationwide over the past five years 
for every one thats publicized there must be easily more 
than a hundred that are not publicized said sandler ive 
asked students does this happen on your campus and im told 
just about every week 
rape by solitary acquaintances also is common studies show 15 
percent to 25 percent of all women undergraduates have been 
physically or psychologically intimidated into having sex against 
their will sandler said 
i dont know if many more instances are occurring now than 20 
years ago its just that the females are more willing and capable 
of speaking out and bringing charges which i think is good 
said durward owen executive director of the pi kappa phi 
fraternity headquartered in charlotte nc 
pi kappa phi which has 6500 members at 142 colleges and 
universities voted six years ago to take a stand against sexual 
abuse owen said a growing number of fraternities have begun 
discussing the problem in the past two years 
we noticed so many instances of athletic team rapes and dorm 
rapes and date rapes being reported he said it appeared that 
many times these things had gone on in the past and were accepted 
at face value 
pi kappa phi mails literature to its chapters and examines the 
issue at regional meetings its chapters often offer seminars with 
other campus groups 
colleges are taking many other tacks 
at brown victims can count on a campuswide help network 
including 24houraday telephone counseling 
simon works to prevent both assaults and sexual misadventures 
bad results that occur because people do not know how to talk about 
sex because they do not make their needs known and because they 
drink too much 
simon repeats the message at freshmen orientation and in a 
sexuality course she addresses student groups including 
fraternities in extremely candid graphic ways using students 
to do role playing using students language 
in 1984 two women at swarthmore college in pennsylvania told a 
dormitory assistant that they had been abused by acquaintances in 
response students produced a consciousnessraising video to be 
shown to freshmen in dorms discussions follow 
since the tape was produced swarthmore has sold about 100 
copies to other schools and organizations 
awareness was heightened at the university of 
californiaberkeley in 1986 after a student said she was raped by 
four ootball players in a dormitory 
no charges were filed and the football players were not 
suspended but they were forced to move out of the dorm do 100 
hours of community service and write apologies to the woman said 
university spokeswoman pat mcbroom 
amid the resulting uproar a facultystudent task force 
investigated womens safety and the campus climate in january 
1987 chancellor ira michael heyman sent a letter to some 30000 
students condemning sexual abuse and noting that no means no 
now rape prevention workshops are held for various campus groups 
there are indications that other schools will be following in 
the footsteps of brown swarthmore and berkeley the association of 
american colleges has issued about 100 recommendations to its 
members on how to prevent rape respond to victims and discipline 
rapists 
in 1987 californias legislature voted to suggest that the 
states colleges and universities adopt codes prohibiting rape and 
setting penalties including suspension or expulsion on conviction 
the resolution also suggests rape prevention seminars for freshmen 
fraternities and sororities 
building on the resolution california assemblywoman lucille 
roybalallard has introduced a bill requiring essentially all 
colleges and universities to follow specific procedures in the 
event of sexual abuse including calling the police when the victim 
allows it 
in new york a report of the governors task force on rape and 
sexual assault has recommended the state university of new york and 
city university of new york develop strong prevention programs 
campusbased surveys have indicated that many students lack an 
understanding of or deny what constitutes a rape said the 
report 
ignorance is only one aspect of the problem mob psychology 
peer pressure and alcohol abuse also contribute 
sandler of the association of american colleges said most gang 
rapists are fraternity brothers or team athletes 
very often these men are simply raping for each other she 
said theyll do something they might not do if they were by 
themselves 
women who report campus attacks often are harassed by the 
rapists and their friends sandler said many drop out or switch 
schools after their attackers start using sexual slurs or other 
intimidation tactics 
shawn johnston a forensic psychologist at the university of 
californiadavis who treats sex offenders said there are times 
such as when alcohol is involved when the line that 
differentiates the consensual or voluntary from a forcible act is 
fairly thin that say womens advocates contributes to a 
blame the victim attitude even by the victim herself 
i dont care if a woman walks into the room raving drunk and 
stark naked its not an excuse to be raped said claire kaplan 
executive director of the washingtonbased national coalition 
against sexual assault 
