<TEXT>
from time to time the economy goes through a 
phase in which longterm goals are abandoned fundamentals are 
forgotten and only the next hour day or week seems to count 
the economy becomes volatile stock prices gyrate inflation 
erupts quick killings are sought and often achieved in real estate 
and securities getrichquick schemes abound and corporations 
wheel and deal 
and then it all evaporates although not until warning signs and 
omens bankruptcies scandals prosecutions become too numerous 
to ignore the old ways come back basics are rediscovered the 
vision is again long term 
like now 
these phases of the cycle are never so sharply defined that they 
produce headlines there are always frayed edges and exceptions to 
the generality but still the pattern can be discerned 
on wall street for example where analysts now talk about a 
companys pricetoearnings ratio rather than the possibility that 
it might be taken over by a larger company with a sudden and 
spectacular rise in price 
in the housing markets where prices are more sensible than they 
were a year ago and where the buyer now buys a house as a place in 
which to live rather than a place in which to invest money for a 
big return 
in corporations where managers are fed up with the destructive 
practice of draining everhigher shortterm profits by refusing to 
waste money on research and capital improvements that make for 
a stronger future 
and where boards of directors are withdrawing those management 
incentives tied to shortterm profits and demanding instead that 
companies be made more competitive in the global marketplace 
at the federal reserve where economic manipulation is in 
disfavor and the goal now is to achieve modest longterm economic 
stability even if it means walking a tightrope over the chasm of 
recession before that goal is achieved 
in organized labor where workers join management to raise 
corporate productivity even if it means forgoing big wage 
increases the notion being that a stronger company conveys greater 
longterm benefits 
in consumer markets where people have begun curtailing their 
propensity to borrow as if there were no tomorrow and are tending 
to save a bit more forgoing purchases that once were almost 
automatic 
these patterns can be discerned over varying lengths of time 
and sometimes patterns of calm and then excitement occur within 
larger patterns but in the marketplace the past two decades 
certainly qualify as a period of volatility 
the stock market erupted time after time then collapsed in cold 
ashes rumors pervaded the market and every day stocks with a 
story were promoted takeovers buyouts new products or demoted 
when they fell into debt 
fundamental analysis often was ignored in the new marketplace 
there was no time for such things why settle for 7 percent annual 
dividends when you might make that in a day on price appreciation 
volatility and change invite creativity new ways of doing 
things short cuts junk bonds trading shenanigans computer 
manipulations taxavoidance schemes a new immorality arises 
until the culprits are caught 
enough of these culprits have been caught in the past couple of 
years to suggest that the easy way the shortcut route doesnt 
pay either on wall street or in corporate management or among 
consumers 
indicative of this is an announcement from a large benefits 
consulting firm after it polled corporations on the types of 
incentives they were offering it offered this report 
longterm incentive plans may be the way of the future 
according to a recent survey 
findings revealed 28 percent of participating companies 
offered longterm incentive plans to executives in 1985 while 40 
percent plan to offer such programs by 1995 
just as it used to be back before all the shortterm business 
began 
</TEXT>
