<TEXT>
a secret security agency created by the 
military regime still operates five years after the generals 
relinquished power to civilians despite the new presidents pledge 
to abolish it 
the national intelligence service a sort of combined fbi and 
cia was synonymous with spying torture censorship and midnight 
knocks on the door under the military governments of 19641985 
its decline accelerated when agents were linked to terrorist 
bombings carried out in an attempt to forestall a return to 
democracy 
when president fernando collor de mello took office mar 15 he 
promised to dismantle the hated agency known as the sni and burn 
its secret files 
the security of the state cannot become the insecurity of the 
citizen said collor who won brazils first direct election for 
president since 1960 
he gave the agency a new name the secretariat of strategic 
affairs and a new civilian director but critics say it still 
collects information about citizens despite laws prohibiting it 
from doing so 
in place of the sni the government created the embryo of a 
political police said walder de goes a political science 
professor at the university of brasilia and an expert on the agency 
the ideological archives were joined with financial 
information about individuals and their police records anywhere in 
the world thats the beginning of a political police 
luis eduardo greenhalgh a lawyer who represented political 
prisoners during military rule said the sni was not 
extinguished just modified some of its agents were returned to 
their military units but most are still spying 
if the government needs dirt on somebody the agency gets it 
everything continues the same 
in 1965 the sni was created as a superintelligence service to 
safeguard national security it spied on citizens tapped 
telephones and tailed alleged leftist opponents of the regime 
as repression increased in the 1960s and early 1970s the agency 
ran covert operations and collected damaging information about 
enemies of the ruling generals 
thousands of brazilians lost their jobs were imprisoned or had 
to flee the country because their names apeareed on the sni list 
the impunity enjoyed by sni agents created disciplinary problems 
within the armed forces and gen golbery do couto e silva who 
formed the agency and was its first director said at one point 
i created a monster 
brazil returned to civilian rule in 1985 but president jose 
sarney chosen by an electoral college under military control did 
not try to curb the armed forces behindthescenes influence 
collor promised a change 
during the 1989 campaign the 40yearold presidential candidate 
referred to the agencys director as a tinpot general the job 
job was a cabinetlevel post 
once in office collor decreed the sni abolished clandestine 
operations would cease he said sni agents would return to the 
regular military and secret archives would be opened to the public 
and destroyed 
to replace the service as insiders called it collor 
created the secretariat of strategic affairs and turned it over to 
pedro paulo leoni ramos a 30yearold businessman and longtime 
friend 
its job was exclusively to provide the president with 
information for political and government policy according to the 
official orders 
the old agency did not die however its files were not 
destroyed and even grew fatter with data from the federal police 
and the internal revenue service 
goes said the new secretariat is more sophisticated than the sni 
ever was 
information and intelligence now are a department of the 
secretariat and continue under the aegis of the military he 
said the other departments of the new agency are strategic policy 
and national defense 
if a crisis were to develop there are now authorities who 
could act like a secret police goes said 
he complained of a lack of outside control over the agency 
noting there is no congressional committee that checks its budget 
or personnel 
like his military predecessors at the sni director ramos is 
highly secretive 
he will not speak to the press and is rarely photographed or 
seen in public several requests by the associated press for an 
interview went unanswered 
the job creates the habit said goes who knows ramos and 
described him as a very capable young man in collors strictest 
confidence and one of the few with direct access to the presidents 
office 
in recent years former members of the sni have revealed some of 
the agencys inner workings and past mistakes 
retired gen helio lemos 74 a former top official said the 
sni had informants in every brazilian embassy and consulate but it 
still didnt even suspect that argentina would invade the falkland 
islands in 1982 
lemos said the sni did not foresee the oil crises of the 1970s 
or the iraniraq war both of which were of great strategic 
importance to brazil an importer of oil and exporter of arms 
adm maximiano da fonseca a former navy minister recalled that 
we got our information from the newspapers 
some generals have grumbled publicly about collors decision to 
put a civilian in charge but goes said the armed forces and 
secretariat now make up a new intelligence network 
the military was worried at first he said but soon the 
spy services of the army navy and air force were expanded and many 
files were duplicated in the event of possible destruction 
he described the combined network as a web so tangled that 
nothing and nobody can escape 
