<TEXT>
in the sprawling suburbia of new jersey 
nearly an hours drive from times square the big broadwaystyle 
musical is alive and flourishing 
it has found a receptive home at the paper mill playhouse a 
onetime summer theater that forsakes conventional strawhat 
offerings for more innovative theater fare produced on a yearly 
budget that now tops 10 million 
the paper mills prominence has risen steadily in the last few 
years primarily because of its savvy mixture of musicals both old 
and new among its productions were a revival of mack and 
mabel a rarely seen jerry herman musical about movie director 
mack sennett and his star mabel norman and a musical version of 
james micheners sayonara 
but the show that gained paper mill a national audience was 
show boat taped at the theater last summer for public 
television and then shown on great performances in the fall 
the revival which starred richard white and eddie bracken will be 
repeated later this year on pbs 
during its current season which ends june 24 paper mill 
produced an opulent revival of fanny with george s irving and 
jose ferrer playing the roles originated on broadway in 1954 by 
walter slezak and ezio pinza and it took on gilbert and sullivan 
in a bigbusiness reworking of one of the duos most famous works 
the mikado rechristened mikado inc it was the theaters 
final offering of a 10month season 
mikado inc which was conceived directed and choreographed 
by robert johanson the theaters artistic director was loosely 
inspired by the gilbert and sullivan operetta the words are all 
new the music was largely reworked for example melodies sung by 
one character in the original are now given to another character 
we try to do an eclectic year says angelo del rossi the 
theaters executive producer and a 27year veteran of the 
playhouse we dont try to do things that are too similar those 
two shows are perfect examples we have no philosophy whatever 
excites us is what we want to do 
paper mill which also does dramas and comedies began mixing 
new musicals with revivals about five years ago 
there wasnt really very much new out there think back to 
what broadway was like then del rossi recalls we do musicals 
well and thought we were in a perfect position to develop new 
musicals 
out of their deliberations came paper mills musical theater 
workshop 
it works like this 
the theater does a reading two performances with script in 
hand of a new work the public is invited and feedback is 
encouraged from both audience and staff 
paper mill does six readings of new material a year its most 
recent reading done in early june was a musical version of the 
jimmy stewart classic its a wonderful life with music by joe 
raposo and lyrics by sheldon harnick 
out of those readings we usually find one show that we like 
and bring it to the next phase the workshop or laboratory phase 
del rossi added at the conclusion of the workshop if we feel it 
deserves a main stage production then we go ahead and do it weve 
done that with sayonara and mikado inc 
del rossi and johanson choose their revivals with care looking 
for good shows that somehow have been neglected 
i try to do things that havent been done continuously like 
my fair lady del rossi says we breathed new life into the 
desert song and the new moon in fact beverly sills saw both 
those productions and picked up our whole artistic staff our 
director our conductor our choreographer and our star brought 
them to city opera and did both of those shows 
i love shows that are romantic have a beautiful love story 
and really have a book as well as something of an epic feeling to 
them johanson said fanny certainly did plus its fun to 
work on something that has no real history people dont know the 
classic production of fanny like they know the classic production 
of a my fair lady or fiddler on the roof 
the paper mill playhouse originally was a paper mill built in 
1790 the long narrow shoebox of a building was turned into a 
theater in 1938 it remained in operation until january 1980 when a 
fire destroyed the stage and auditorium 
we were not quite sure we were going to come back said del 
rossi about the dark days following the fire i didnt want to 
come back as the old paper mill playhouse i wanted to return as a 
new theater with new ideas 
reconstruction wasnt easy in 1980 the interest rate was 165 
percent the theater had no money and was surviving from show to 
show 
it took a year for the trustees to approve rebuilding and then 
almost two years to actually do it the final cost was nearly 9 
million much of the money raised by del rossi and his staff from 
corporations foundations and from the state 
from a meager subscription base that would vary between 2000 
and 6000 paper mill today has 43000 subscribers for its 10month 
season plays run five weeks and musicals are booked for sixweek 
engagements 
paper mill now has a permanent staff of 40 people who help put 
together each show the scenery is designed and built there and 
although costumes are often rented the theater is developing 
facilities to do its own costumes 
del rossi encourages creators of new work not to be be 
intimidated by size 
we are one of the few theaters when we put the search out for 
new material that say dont restrict yourselves because of size 
we want anything that is good and not to have authors afraid to 
send us something that has a cast of 24 people most of our musical 
casts at paper mill are 30 to 40 people 
the theater is also commissioning new works for the stage 
mikado inc was one such commission among other commissioned 
projects which could turn up in a year or two are a science 
fiction musical and a musical about the last princess of hawaii 
next year were thinking about doing an opera but not like the 
met or the new york city opera would do it del rossi said but 
we want to do it the way a musical theater would do it we just 
take different approaches to things 
