<DOCNO> AP900613-0233 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the securities and exchange commissions 
attempt to prevent corporations from creating different classes of 
stock with unequal voting rights has been thwarted by a federal 
appeals court 
a threejudge appeals panel in washington ruled unanimously that 
the sec exceeded its authority when it imposed a socalled one 
share one vote rule 
that supported the contention of the business roundtable an 
association of the nations top corporations which claimed the sec 
rule interfered with the traditional role of the individual states 
in regulating corporate governance 
the sec had contended that its federal mandate to protect 
investors in publicly traded companies gave it the right to impose 
the one share one vote rule 
but the us circuit court of appeals for the district of 
columbia said the sec went beyond its congressionally mandated 
authority to oversee the financial markets 
because the rule directly controls the substantive allocation 
of powers among classes of shareholders we find it in excess of 
the commissions authority the panel said in a 21page opinion 
written by circuit judge stephen f williams concurring with 
williams were circuit judges james l buckley and harry t edwards 
i was disappointed said richard g ketchum head of the 
secs division of market regulation sec officials will have to 
review the opinion before deciding whether to appeal he said 
the united shareholders association a washingtonbased 
stockholders rights group founded by t boone pickens also 
bemoaned the decision as a major blow to americas 47 million 
shareholders and the entire freeenterprise system 
usa director ralph whitworth urged the sec to appeal the ruling 
to the supreme court 
the head of the roundtables corporate governance task force 
hailed the decision though 
american shareholders won an important victory today said 
bruce atwater who is also chief executive officer of general 
mills the court has resoundingly affirmed their right to 
determine for themselves what kinds of equities best serve their 
interests 
the business roundtable argued that the sec had overstepped its 
authority and was trying to regulate how companies are run a 
traditional role of the states the states of ohio delaware 
kentucky michigan idaho pennsylvania wyoming nebraska north 
carolina missouri georgia and west virginia had filed court 
papers supporting the groups stance 
the roundtable is an association of 200 companies that includes 
american express co xerox corp citicorp and general mills 
its a very important decision that limits the secs attempt 
to regulate corporate governance said attorney robert d 
rosenbaum who represented the group in oral arguments last 
november before the appeals court 
the appeals court found that sec authority to compel full 
corporate disclosure to shareholders doesnt extend to what 
shareholders can decide rosenbaum said 
the sec rule in question rule 19c4 was adopted in july 1988 
it prohibited publicly traded corporations from weakening the 
voting power of existing stockholders by issuing new classes of 
stock with superior or supervoting rights 
in filings with the appeals court last fall the sec claimed 
that without the curb shareholders could be stripped of their 
ability to participate in management and confidence in the 
securities markets could be impaired 
rule 19c4 allowed the sec to bar an offending companys stock 
from being listed on any stock exchange that it regulated or with 
the national association of securities dealers stock quotation 
system nasdaq 
the sec claimed congress intended it to have such authority to 
ensure that exchanges didnt lower their listing standards to 
attract more corporate stock listings 
but the appeals court said that intent only concerned the secs 
authority to govern exchanges and quote systems not corporations 
to argue that congresss equal regulation mandate supports 
sec control over corporate governance through national listing 
standards is to gamble that the court will accept a commission spin 
on a statutory fragment without even a glance at its context 
said the court adding wrong court bad gamble 
the secs ketchum said he did not think the ruling would cause 
the nations stock exchanges to lower their listing requirements 
</TEXT>
