<TEXT>
rescue crews working on air bagequipped 
cars should disconnect the vehicles batteries to assure the safety 
devices dont accidentally deploy a fire official says 
automakers began installing air bags en masse late last year 
because of governmental regulation requiring passive restraint 
systems on 1990 and later model cars 
the devices are standard equipment on all of chrysler corps 
us made cars about half of ford motor cos and about 15 percent 
of general motors corps 
this week firefighters from around the united states and canada 
are at the gm proving grounds west of detroit using crashtest cars 
to practice roadside rescue techniques and learn about new 
technology in cars including air bags 
some of firefighters said tuesday there was concern about armed 
air bags deploying during rescue operations 
you dont put yourself between an undeployed air bag and the 
victim said ken jones of owen sound ontario and a member of 
the ontario fire marshals office the information about the 
new technology of the cars hasnt been disseminated to us 
the big three automakers have issued owners and dealer service 
manuals describing how the devices work precautions to take while 
working near them and disclaimers saying failure to follow 
directions could result in injury 
if somebody is there with their nose against the bag and the 
thing goes off i guess somebody might get injured said gm 
spokesman don postma 
the cardinal rule automakers say is to disable the cars 
electrical system which powers the air bag the device designed 
to be used with manual lap and shoulder seat belts is a large 
pillow flattened and stored in a steering wheel or dash board it 
inflates in a tenth of a second and begins deflating immediately 
other passive restraint systems include an automatic shoulder 
belt on a track used with a manual lap belt and an automatic lap 
and shoulder belt system 
in a garage disabling a cars electrical system along with the 
air bag is simply a matter of unbolting battery cables at a crash 
scene things are more complicated 
if it is difficult to locate the battery or determine if its 
cables are intact then automakers recommend mechanics and rescuers 
go under the steering column to disconnect the air bag 
