<DOCNO> AP900613-0250 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the chinese laundry the italian produce stand 
the jewish delicatessen the irish bar are old cliches of american 
life more recently the korean greengrocer has joined the list 
aspiring to business ownership to be ones own boss to be 
independent to control ones destiny to create a future for ones 
family all are deeply rooted in the american ethic 
but what happened to black entrepreneurship 
blacks and hispanics make up nearly 20 percent of the 
population but they own less than 5 percent of the countrys small 
businesses and many of them are extremely small 
but a report by the businesshigher education forum made up of 
chief executives of major american colleges universities and 
corporations suggests the opportunity for minority entrepreneurs 
now may be better than at any time since the turn of the 
century 
they view the racial climate as having changed sufficiently and 
the economic climate as now favoring smallbusinesses that can 
adapt to quickly changing markets meanwhile the black 
middleclass market has swelled 
throughout the 87page report however it becomes clear that 
still another factor might be at work a new sense of urgency by 
the establishment educators and executives included that black 
entrepreneurship should get a helping hand 
in tracing the history of black enterpreneurship the report 
cites the work of bart landry a stanford university sociologist 
who describes the existence of blackowned enterprises even before 
the emancipation 
after the civil war such businesses flourished the report 
states 
building on skills acquired during slavery black 
entrepreneurs worked metal repair harness and leathergoods 
managed hotels and rooming houses catered and operated grocery 
stores 
but it states these enterprises were almost completely 
obliterated during the reconstruction or the period of economic 
and governmental rebuilding after the civil war 
still when the fourth atlanta university conference on the 
negro in business met in 1898 more than 1900 black businessmen 
participated and two years later booker t washington founded the 
national business league 
but the report relates thrift and individual enterprise were 
weak reeds on which to rely in the year 1900 blackowned 
business encountered selective white racism and the north 
industrialized while the south was held back 
only certain enterprises remained open to blacks the report 
describes how black business owners cut hair provided meals 
cleaned and pressed clothes and buried the dead all required 
little capital 
now almost a century later the forum which many people will 
identify as the establishment believe the causes of the problem 
and its solution is clear minority business problems it says are 
often 
problems of access to financial institutions and to 
community networks that might provide financing to begin a 
business finance an initial inventory andf obtain equipment and 
space 
many ethnic minorities avoided some degree of these problems 
even financial ones because of strong family and community 
structures and because of institutions brought from the old 
country blacks have not always had them 
the forum makes many important recommendations in educational 
and business areas few of which seem more important than in the 
area of capital development 
in particular it suggests that corporations investigate three 
related strategies of capital assistance 
1 creating partnerships with local banks and community 
developoment groups to bring business back to the inner city 
2 depositing a small percentage of corporate assets in the 
banks that form the cornerstone of these venture to be available 
for mortgage and business loans 
3 investing for profit directly in the venture capital efforts 
of community development efforts 
every little bit will help according to the report signed by 
task force cochairmen steven mason of the mead corporation and 
clifton wharton of the teachers insurance and annuity association 
indeed it might take very little 
the report stresses that investing a very small amount of the 
capital controlled by major corporations a fraction of one 
percent can exert an enormous force for good in supporting these 
community based organizations 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

