<TEXT>
gold futures prices flirted with 350 an ounce wednesday 
dropping to within 50 cents of that psychologically important level 
before rebounding to 352 the lowest daily settlement on new 
yorks commodity exchange in nearly four years 
silver futures also fell sharply in new york reflecting 
investor preference for stocks and bonds over precious metals 
analysts said 
on other commodity markets grains and soybeans retreated oil 
futures rose and livestock and meat futures were mixed 
gold futures settled 370 to 490 lower with the contract for 
delivery in june down 370 at 352 a troy ounce the lowest 
settlement of a comex gold contract since july 30 1986 silver 
finished 103 cents to 131 cents lower with june at 4915 a troy 
ounce the lowest silver futures price since may 19 1986 
the more actively traded july silver contract finished at 4933 
an ounce 
don tierney an analyst with the commodities brokerage stanley 
bell amp co traced golds decline to expectations that the 10 am 
edt closing gold price fix from london would come in at 350 or 
lower following heavy middle eastern selling of bullion just prior 
to the london close 
instead london dealers fixed their closing price at 35050 
which eased selling pressure in new york he said 
the magic psychological level held at least for today 
tierney said he added though that the gold market still looked 
weak from a technical standpoint 
a move below 350 an ounce probably would spark further selling 
possibly pressing golds price as low as 335 or even 320 before 
significant buying surfaces said bernard savaiko senior metals 
analyst with painewebber inc 
savaiko said strong bond and stock markets are siphoning 
investor interest away from the metals 
as long as you have strong interest in paper assets youre 
going to have gold sagging as investors forego precious metals or 
sell them he said 
in other trading corn futures fell steeply on the chicago board 
of trade amid profittaking after a government report confirmed 
perceptions of a shrinking national corn stockpile 
most other grain and soybean futures finished slightly lower 
after hovering near unchanged for most of the session 
in a report released after the close of trading tuesday the 
agriculture department raised its estimate of corn exports for the 
marketing year ending aug 31 by 50 million bushels and accordingly 
lowered its projection for the corn stockpile next september by 50 
million bushels to 128 billion bushels 
wheat futures settled unchanged to 2 cents lower with july at 
334 a bushel corn was 2 cents to 4 cents lower with july at 
290 a bushel oats were 1 cents to 2 cents lower with july at 
143 a bushel soybeans were 2 cents lower to 2 cents higher with 
july at 606 a bushel 
energy futures rallied late in the session on the new york 
mercantile exchange following news that the organization of 
petroleum exporting countries had trimmed crudeoil production by 
700000 barrels per day to 229 million during the first two weeks 
of june 
west texas intermediate crude oil settled 1 cent to 12 cents 
higher with july at 1758 a barrel heating oil was 20 cent to 
50 cent higher with july at 4857 cents a gallon unleaded 
gasoline was 30 cent to 57 cent higher with july at 5885 cents a 
gallon 
on the chicago mercantile exchange cattle futures rallied 
moderately amid market talk that top steer prices in the texas 
panhandle and western kansas rose 50 cents to 7750 cents a pound 
pork futures were mixed as weaker cash prices for pork products 
offset gains in the cash hog market 
live cattle futures finished 10 cent lower to 57 cent higher 
with june at 7677 cents a pound feeder cattle were unchanged to 
18 cent higher with august at 8497 cents a pound live hogs were 
40 cent lower to 05 cent higher with june at 6417 cents a pound 
frozen pork bellies were 05 cent lower to 10 cent higher with 
july at 7045 cents a pound 
