<TEXT>
americans are increasingly worried about their 
ability to pay their longterm bills and as far as their 
pocketbooks view the 1990s with pessimism according to a survey 
to be released thursday 
especially anxious about money are the nations baby boomers 
according to the study conducted by the gallup organization for the 
atlantabased international association for financial planners 
the survey results confirmed concerns financial planners have 
seen developing over the last few years said robert a hewitt 
chairman of the iafp 
according to the survey 46 percent of the respondents expressed 
worry about their ability to meet all of their financial 
responsibilities and 52 percent said they were concerned about 
outliving their retirement savings 
but among those between the ages of 35 and 44 59 percent were 
worried about their ability to meet financial responsibilities and 
62 percent were concerned about outliving their savings the survey 
said 
eightysix percent of the all respondents said college costs 
have risen beyond the reach of most american families and 86 
percent said they believe severe inflation is likely to be a 
problem in this decade 
because of these type of concerns the survey said 61 percent 
of the overall respondents said they were less inclined to take 
financial risks than during the 1980s 
the survey conducted in april among 1058 households in a 
random sample and an additional 600 with incomes of at least 
50000 had a margin of error of plus or minus 3 percent 
hewitt called the 3544 age group triple squeeze boomers 
because they are increasingly having to deal with the costs of 
raising children and taking care of their aging parents as well as 
tending to their own needs 
all of a sudden they have this discretionary income and 
discover gosh im going to have to pay for college for little 
johnny hewitt said 
