<TEXT>
raising a new red flag over californias 
thrift industry homefed bank said its bad loans and foreclosed 
properties rose by 81 million in may 
homefed reported similar news in april and on tuesday it said 
more problems are likely in coming months mainly because of 
outofstate loans 
homefed is the chief subsidiary of san diegobased homefed corp 
and californias seventhbiggest thrift 
nonperforming assets now total 579 million or 31 percent of 
its 18 billion in assets bad loans rose 72 million to 315 
million in may foreclosed real estate by 9 million to 264 
million 
homefed reported a 44 million increase in nonperforming assets 
in april mainly because of loans on a florida apartment complex 
robert f adelizzi homefeds chief executive said the biggest 
problem in may was a default on 54 million in loans on california 
commercial property the loans to an individual adelizzi declined 
to name already had been restructured he said 
it is not indicative of any weakness in the california 
economy although its pretty clear that certain portions of 
commercial market are problems in california as well as 
nationwide adelizzi said in a telephone interview 
in spite of the states strong economy californias sampls have 
racked up some big losses in the past few years with outofstate 
lending and junk bonds at the top of the list of bad investments 
adelizzi said homefed had been making headway in paring its 
level of bad loans and foreclosures which peaked at 592 million 
in september 1989 
but the last two months results combined with weakness in 
commercial markets nationwide and apartment markets outside 
california have tainted the outlook he said 
it is probable that the level of nonperforming assets will 
increase further in june and our goal of reducing these assets 
below 400 million by yearend 1990 will be extremely difficult to 
achieve adelizzi said 
all big loans at homefed are under a special review he 
suggested there may be more problems particularly with 
outofstate loans saying another 140 million in loans are 30 
days or more overdue loans are classified as nonaccrual or bad 
when they are 90 days overdue 
campbell chaney a thrift analyst with sutro amp co in san 
francisco said the disclosures raise questions about all of 
californias banks and sampls particularly those with out of state 
loans 
i think what it tells me is that california is not infallible 
despite what people say about how well its economy is doing and its 
insulation chaney said 
