<TEXT>
the securities and exchange commission wants 
to know if the laws governing mutual funds and other investment 
companies should be overhauled and if so how 
the sec which regulates stocks bonds and the exchanges that 
trade in them voted unanimously wednesday to seek public comment 
on updating regulation of investment companies 
the last significant amendments to those regulations were made 
in 1970 
investment companies manage pooled funds of small investors 
money for a fee some like mutual funds are openended investors 
can buy into or sell out of these funds when they wish and 
depending on those investment flows the funds managers buy or 
sell stocks and bonds 
others are closedend funds such as investment trusts these 
funds have an investment pool of a fixed size and issue shares 
backed by that pool that can be traded like a corporations 
the commission voted to ask for public comment on several topics 
including the internationalization of the securities markets 
distribution of openend companies closedend funds and 
repurchases of shares it also asks the public to put in its own 
two cents about what changes should be made 
in other matters the sec voted to seek public comment on 
proposed rules that would 
close a loophole in the investment company act of 1940 and 
require investment companies dealing in foreign securities to 
either maintain records in english or at least in the united states 
allow investment companies to save time and money by sending 
out summary prospectuses initially to investors who would then 
request the entire prospectus often numbering a hundred or more 
pages if they were interested 
</TEXT>
