<TEXT>
the senate voted wednesday to restrict logging 
and set aside 673000 acres as a protected area in alaskas huge 
tongass national forest 
the bill would modify two longterm harvesting contracts to 
protect old growth timber and end a 40 million annual incentive to 
high levels of harvesting 
the unanimous vote came after senators set aside a disputed 
amendment that would have required the us forest service to trade 
mining rights in the greens creek area of admiralty island in 
southeastern alaska 
the exchange with the nativealaskan owned sealaska corp would 
have given the government other mining rights and land including 
the last 6000 acres of oldgrowth timber on admiralty island 
under an agreement worked out among senators the secretary of 
agriculture will try to speed up negotiations on a voluntary land 
and miningrights trade also the senate energy and commerce 
committee will hold hearings beginning june 28 to find out if the 
items to be traded are of comparable value 
backers say the overall bill is necessary to protect the 
167millionacre forest which is larger than west virginia the 
forest is one of the few remaining temperate rain forests in the 
world 
the oldgrowth portions host large concentrations of bald eagles 
and grizzly bears the forest also is home to valuable salmon 
spawning grounds 
critics said changes will cost jobs in the timberdependent 
local economy but they say they prefer the senate version to the 
stricter version adopted by the house almost a year ago 
alaska gov steve cowper said wednesday the senate bill was a 
balanced solution and described himself as especially pleased 
with a provision for nologging buffer strips along fishbearing 
streams 
this is a national forest not a national park said sen 
ted stevens ralaska when debate began tuesday people live and 
work in this forest and a good number of them almost 3400 people 
make their living solely from cutting and processing the trees that 
are harvested in the tongass 
their interests should be balanced against the desire to leave 
this forest uncut 
wednesdays debate centered on an amendment by sen jake garn 
rutah to give sealaska owned by descendants of alaskas original 
inhabitants mining rights to 18000 acres at greens creek 
in exchange the forest service would have received mining 
rights to 10000 acres on admiralty along with 1860 acres of 
surface lands and 10 percent of sealaskas income from the mining 
venture 
sen howard metzenbaum dohio tried to block the amendment 
saying the government might be giving away rights to land rich in 
silver gold lead and zinc he said the real beneficiaries would 
be mining companies such as kennecott in garns home state which 
run a successful mine for sealaska within greens creek 
metzenbaum called the 18000 acres the donut around a highly 
profitable hole the existing mine 
lets not tie up tongass reform with this giveaway 
metzenbaum said 
an amendment on the exchange will be taken up again when house 
and senate negotiators work on a compromise 
the bill would leave 14 million acres or about 8 percent of the 
total forest available for logging rather than the current 17 
million acres about 10 percent 
the house bill would cancel rather than modify the 50year 
contracts the government has with alaska pulp co and louisiana 
pacificketchikan 
critics say the two companies have monopolized timber and 
violated antitrust and labor laws they say canceling the 50year 
sweetheart deals would open the area to competition from other 
firms 
the senate bill would 
delete a 40 million appropriation for roadbuilding and other 
timber sale preparation activities 
end the requirement that the forest service provide for sale 
45 billion board feet of tongass timber each decade instead the 
service would be obligated to seek to meet market demand for 
timber 
protect hundreds of thousands of more acres of land from 
logging including buffer zones along streams 
</TEXT>
