<TEXT>
sorting out responsibility and liability for 
the oil tanker explosion off the texas coast illustrates the 
problems of policing a global industry 
the norwegian owned and registered mega borg was staffed by 
indians and chartered by a french oil company to carry crude from 
angola to the united states for processing 
the series of explosions that ripped the 886foot tanker early 
saturday focused attention on us legislation to improve oil 
tanker safety which has bogged down in a housesenate conference 
committee the accident occurred as some of the mega borgs cargo 
was being loaded onto another tanker in the gulf of mexico 
but even if the pending oil tanker legislation became law it 
might not have any effect on accidents like that on board the mega 
borg though the tanker is sitting less than 60 miles off the coast 
of texas it is in international waters 
that means the borgs norwegian owners may not be legally held 
liable for any damage to the us coastline lawsuits over such 
liability and how far a countrys jurisdiction extends sometimes 
get held up for years suits over the 1979 amoco cadiz spill off 
the french coast are still mired in courts 
the us legislation crafted after last years exxon valdez 
accident in alaska includes a provision requiring us tankers to 
have double hulls to prevent spills but some house factions want 
to exempt the huge tankers that unload cargo offshore onto smaller 
vessels a procedure used at nearly every us oil port 
also any us legislation will be effective only in the united 
states and its waters unlike the airline industry which is 
subject to regulations recognized around the world the shipping 
business isnt scrutinized by central government agencies 
the shipping industry in general is not many peoples top 
priority in terms of capitol hill and other places said paul 
henning a spokesman for omi corp an independent tanker owner in 
new york its difficult to get attention focused on issues at 
times because of that 
as the fire raged on the mega borg monday one of the worlds 
oil giants royal dutch shell group announced that it would use 
only one louisiana port for all the crude oil it ships to the 
united states in tankers it owns 
the louisiana offsore oil port an offshore terminal known as 
the loop is the oil terminal in the lower 48 states capable of 
handling very large crude carriers 
at other oil ports supertanker cargoes must be transferred to 
smaller ships the process that was underway when the mega borg 
exploded but at the louisiana facility big tankers can unload 
without ever coming ashore 
shell said it took the action because of the liability risks 
the exxon valdez made it clear what happens when you have a spill 
and the enormous liabilities you can face said norm altstedter 
a spokesman in new york for the anglodutch conglomerate 
following the alaska spill the nations worst exxon was 
indicted in february on five federal charges they included 
violating the port and waterways safety act the dangerous cargo 
act the clean water act and the migratory bird treaty act and 
illegally discharging oil 
prosecutors said they would seek at least 700 million in 
penalties from exxon under a law that allows recovery of twice the 
amount of proven losses 
though other oil companies are studying shells decision the 
initial impact appears to be negligible the new policy does not 
include any shipments by shell oil co the groups us 
subsidiary or cargoes carried by tankers that royal dutch shell 
charters from other companies about 75 percent of its shipments 
to the united states 
exxon corp which has been under fire for the valdez accident 
has no current plans to restrict the movements of its tankers 
spokesman bill smith said 
elf aquitaine petroleum co the french company that had 
chartered the mega borg is considering adopting a policy similar 
to shells said a spokesman in houston who asked not to be 
identified further 
some shipping insiders said they believed the shell move was an 
attempt to pressure congress which is considering the use of 
international agreements to determine liability in a spill 
those agreements which have not been ratified by the united 
states provide up to 260 million from an international 
compensation fund to clean up a spill according to house backers 
of the measure 
the us has not yet ratified the international conventions 
which limit liability said altstedter the shell spokesman 
and theres no limitation on liability 
top transportation department officials the head of the coast 
guard and members of congress from texas urged congress to 
subscribe to the international limits which is a chief point of 
disagreement between the two houses over the pending legislation 
the house wants the limits the senate version of the bill would 
let state law govern such situations 
the house and the senate have to reach agreement on this 
legislation and this nation is exposed until that is done said 
transportation secretary samual skinner 
the commandant of the coast guard rear adm william kime said 
the united states dodged the bullet in the texas accident 
because the owners of the mega borg were cooperating in the cleanup 
and the investigation 
</TEXT>
