<TEXT>
the bush administration has decided not to 
impose economic sanctions against india for its barriers to 
american investment and sales by us insurance companies an 
administration official said wednesday 
the official speaking on condition that he not be named said 
the decision had been made to continue pressing for removal of the 
barriers as part of global freetrade talks rather than imposing 
economic retaliation now 
us trade representative carla hills met with indias new 
ambassador to washington abid hussain on wednesday to inform him 
of the action sources said 
the administration was facing a deadline of deciding by june 16 
whether to boost tariffs on imports from india into the united 
states or take some other form of trade retaliation because of 
indias refusal to negotiate over the issue 
the case against india involves that countrys barriers to 
foreign investment and its refusal to allow american insurance 
companies to do business in the country 
india was one of three countries placed on a trade hit list 
last year by the bush administration for erecting the most 
offensive trade barriers against american products 
the other two countries japan and brazil both negotiated on 
the issues which landed them on the list and reached agreements 
with the united states to remove the offending barriers 
however india has refused to negotiate under threat of us 
sanctions which are provided by a section of the 1988 trade law 
known as super 301 
while the decision removes the possibility of economic 
retaliation for this year the administration has already announced 
that it was naming india for its offending trade barriers under a 
second round of the super 301 process that will not conclude until 
june 1991 
that decision announced on april 27 triggered an avalanche of 
criticism in congress because of the administrations refusal to 
cite japan once again 
the administration contended that japan had negotiated in good 
faith to remove barriers to sales of american satellites super 
computers and wood products in japan 
the administration also pledged to press forward with separate 
discussions on broadranging structural trade barriers with japan 
however there have been complaints in recent days that the 
talks with japan on structural impediments to trade had bogged 
down a final report on these talks is scheduled to be issued in 
july 
senate finance committee chairman lloyd bentsen dtexas 
accused japan on tuesday of stonewalling on the trade issue and 
warned that his committee which has jurisdiction over trade 
matters wold insist that more be done 
sens max baucus dmont bob packwood roregon and john 
danforth rmo were even more blunt writing a letter to hills 
warning that congress may have no choice but to respond with 
retaliatory legislation if japan is not more forthcoming 
the structural barriers talks are focusing on such various ways 
the japanese can make their economy more receptive to imports as 
well as ways the united states can dampen its appetite for foreign 
products 
</TEXT>
